<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,613,919]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<bibRefCitation author="Macquart" box="[151,353,613,639]" pageId="42" pageNumber="44" refString="Macquart, J. (1838) Dipteres exotiques nouveaux ou peu connus. Vol. 1, Pt. 2. Paris, pp. 5 - 207." type="journal article" year="1838">
Macquart (
<number box="[283,344,613,639]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1838.0">1838</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName box="[489,696,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ceraturgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis box="[489,696,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Ceraturgus niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
“de l’Amérique boréale.” 
<bibRefCitation author="Walker" box="[1026,1199,613,639]" pageId="42" pageNumber="45" refString="Walker, F. (1854) List of the specimens of dipterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Part VI. Supplement II. Trustees of the British Museum, London, pp. 331 - 506." type="book chapter" year="1854">
Walker (
<number box="[1130,1191,613,639]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1854.0">1854</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
later listed it from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,245,653,679]" name="Mexico" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[256,503,653,679]" pageId="42" pageNumber="45" refString="Osten Sacken, C. R. (1878) Catalogue of the described Diptera of North America, second edition. Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections 270, 276 pp." type="book">
Osten Sacken (
<number box="[433,494,653,679]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1878.0">1878</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
transferred it to 
<taxonomicName box="[700,820,653,678]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Taracticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[700,820,653,678]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Taracticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without explanation. 
<bibRefCitation author="Brauer" box="[1080,1247,653,679]" pageId="42" pageNumber="44" refString="Brauer, F. (1883) Ueber die Gattung Isopogon Loew. Wiener Entomologische Zeitung, 2, 53 - 56." type="journal article" year="1883">
Brauer (
<number box="[1177,1238,653,679]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1883.0">1883</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
did not find the stout, enlarged spine at the apex of the fore tibia that is found in 
<taxonomicName box="[913,1033,693,718]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Taracticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[913,1033,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Taracticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He and 
<bibRefCitation box="[1143,1337,693,719]" pageId="42" pageNumber="45" refString="Williston, S. W. (1884) On the North American Asilidae (Dasypogoninae, Laphrinae), with a new genus of Syrphidae. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 11, 1 - 35." type="journal article">
Williston (
<number box="[1267,1328,693,719]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1884.0">1884</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
felt that 
<taxonomicName box="[151,248,733,758]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ceraturgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis box="[151,248,733,758]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
did not belong in 
<taxonomicName box="[465,585,733,758]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Taracticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,585,733,758]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Taracticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Macquart’s (
<number box="[751,812,733,759]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1838.0">1838</number>
) illustrations show five antennomeres, with the third flagellomere longer than the scape, and much shorter than the first flagellomere. He described it as a small (about 
<quantity box="[235,327,813,839]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
long), black species with grayish yellow face and front, yellowish mystax, yellowish wings, having white spots on some of the abdominal segments. Macquart’s 
<taxonomicName box="[965,1063,853,878]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ceraturgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis box="[965,1063,853,878]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be a species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Taracticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Taracticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but no known North American species of 
<taxonomicName box="[695,827,893,918]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ceraturgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[695,827,893,918]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Ceraturgus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fits its description.
</paragraph>
